lacksmithing apprenticeship, a difficult passage to Canada, an unconventional marriage, and the peaks and valleys of her political career. In Eliza, Akenson offers readers a correction to the male-dominated historical record and an unforgettable literary heroine.Shortlisted for the Trillium Prize when it was released in 1990, this classic Canadian novel has only gained relevance in the thirty years since. At Face Value offers a window into the past and a mirror for the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeministszCanadavFiction. 0aLegislatorszCanadavFiction. 0aMale impersonatorszCanadavFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aEliza McCormack.  aIndigenous.  aIrish.  aJohn White.  aMoll Flanders.  aParliament.  aTory.  aapprenticeship.  abackbencher.  ablacksmith.  acholera.  aempowerment.  agender.  amarriage.  anovel.  apassage.  apost-Confederation.  aself.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801240540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228012405423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228012405/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles